{{Cleanup}}
[[File:Smuggler_Baron_SWRPGAD.png|thumb|right|200px|A human smuggler baroness]]
{{Quote|I think it's occasionally good for us to remember that being a smuggler doesn't necessarily require one to be a barbarian, too.|[[Talon Karrde]], to [[Mara Jade Skywalker|Mara Jade]]|<ref name="Heir to the Empire">''[[Heir to the Empire]]''</ref>}}
A '''smuggler''', also known by the euphemism '''free trader''',<ref name="TLAOTH">{{FFG|story=The Long Arm of the Hutt|book=Star Wars: Edge of the Empire Beginner Game|text=''Star Wars: Edge of the Empire'' Beginner Game}}</ref> was someone who engaged in the clandestine shipment of goods or people to prevent taxation or some other impediment. The goods shipped were often highly illegal or banned in some [[Sector/Legends|sectors]]. Weapon smugglers were referred to as '''gun runners'''.

==Profession==
{{Quote| Smugglers can handle just about anything-they fly through asteroid fields, play tag with nebulas and space storms, and they can land on anything. Nothing fazes a good smuggler. I've seen them land ships while fighting uneven gravity fields on asteroids barely bigger than their vessels. Gravity shifts, atmospheric turbulence, sandstorms, blizzards, typhoons...you name it, they know how to handle it.|[[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Lando Calrissian]], to [[Bria Tharen]]|<ref name="Rebel Dawn">''[[Rebel Dawn]]''</ref>}}
[[File:Smuggler_TOR.png|thumb|left|160px|A smuggler around the time of the [[Great Galactic War]]]]
Smuggling, while a part of [[The galaxy/Legends|galactic]] trade for many years in the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]], absolutely thrived under the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire's]] strict control of goods. The nationalization of former [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Separatist]] companies' assets, including their vast [[Merchant/Legends|merchant]] [[Fleet/Legends|fleets]], greatly increased smuggling's appeal—and demand. By [[3 ABY/Legends|3 ABY]], smuggling had become so common that Imperial officers often looked the other way if they found a smuggling outfit. For example, [[Admiral/Legends|Admiral]] [[Kendal Ozzel/Legends|Kendal Ozzel]], dismissed the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel]] outpost [[Echo Base/Legends|Echo Base]] on [[Hoth/Legends|Hoth]] as a smuggling operation when reports of its location arrived from an [[Arakyd Industries/Legends|Arakyd]] [[Viper probe droid/Legends|Viper probe droid]]. The fact that many smugglers operated in support of the Rebellion and channeled funds to them made such distinctions even more difficult.

==Smuggled goods==
{{Quote|You're a smuggler, are you not? Along with speed, your speciality is concealment.|[[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]], to [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]]|<ref name="Star Wars (radio)">[[Star Wars (radio)|''Star Wars'' radio drama]]</ref>}}
[[File:DynamicDuo-Chewbacca4.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Famous smuggler duo Han Solo and Chewbacca, with their ship, the ''Millennium Falcon'']]
By far the most commonly smuggled substances were varieties of [[Spice/Legends|spice]]. Although most kinds of spice were psychoactive drugs, and most forms were illegal under the Empire, the government's main concern was not to stem the flow of spice, but to collect taxes from its shipment and distribution through legitimate channels. Weapons were another commonly smuggled commodity within the Empire, whose bureaucracy strictly controlled weapons availability in order to prevent criminals and insurgents, in particular the Rebel Alliance, from becoming significant threats. Other cargo for smugglers included [[Chak-root/Legends|chak-root]], stolen merchandise, and even clear water (smuggled to [[Rampa III]]). In extreme situations, smugglers delivered standard resources or food; for example, on [[Abregado-rae/Legends|Abregado-rae]], smugglers supplied Separatists after a new regime stopped all food transports to the Separatists in the mountains in hopes of stamping out opposition. During his time as a smuggler, Jolee Bindo stole from the rich and smuggled in the stolen goods to the people of the Ukatis system, due to the blockade imposed by its own king. Some smugglers, such as [[Mirax Terrik Horn|Mirax Terrik]], specialized in finding rare and sometimes illegal goods or artifacts and delivering them to their clients who hoped to avoid using "official means." In addition, sometimes live droids were smuggled through areas such as transport terminals, including that of the space station belonging to the Star Tours interstellar travel agency, with success largely because of [[G2-9T/Legends|G2-9T]], the security droid responsible for baggage checks, being incompetent at his job.<ref name="ST2">''[[Star Tours: The Adventures Continue]]''</ref>

==Stance==
[[File:Smuggling_compartments.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Many [[Starship/Legends|ships]] contained smuggling compartments.]]
A common stereotype in [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] was that smugglers were usually [[Corellian/Legends|Corellian]], and indeed, there were no shortages of Corellian smugglers, but smuggling was carried out by various freight carriers and criminal organizations of all species and planetary origins. Even members of the Imperial bureaucracy and military establishment had their own smuggling organizations, while other smugglers (such as [[Prince/Legends|Prince]] [[Xizor/Legends|Xizor]] of Black Sun) were important players in legitimate galactic business. Fringe elements like the [[Black Sun/Legends|Black Sun]] established large networks dedicated to evading Imperial forces within the galaxy. Another set of major players in illegal trade were the [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]] [[Kajidic/Legends|Kajidics]], vast criminal organizations based around the clan structure of the Hutts. The Hutts controlled a [[Hutt Space/Legends|region]] of the galaxy in the [[Mid Rim/Legends|Mid]] and [[Outer Rim Territories/Legends|Outer Rim]] which maintained independence from the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]], and later great autonomy within the Empire; this allowed them to recruit [[Pilot/Legends|pilots]] and buy ships for use in smuggling with a minimum of scrutiny, while possessing safe locations for their pilots to use. Some planets were controlled by the Hutts but nominally within the Imperial sphere of influence, such as [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]], which provided excellent locations to secretly funnel shipments, pilots, and supplies into Imperial space without arousing suspicion.

==Common problems for smugglers==
[[File:Contraband_by_Alejandro-Mirabal.png|thumb|right|180px|A smuggler being controlled by an [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] patrol]]
{{Quote|Well, that's the real trick, isn't it? And it's going to cost you something extra.|[[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]], to [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] and [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]]|<ref name="Episode 4">{{Film|IV}}</ref>}}
Smugglers had to worry about attacks from [[Pirate/Legends|pirates]] and opportunists who would attempt to steal their cargo, meaning that smugglers needed to avoid some of the most lawless [[Star system/Legends|star systems]] to remain safe. Also, because they were smuggling contraband, they had no hope of help from Imperial/Republic forces and could not seek the protection of the galactic authorities. Most smugglers developed keen skills to avoid trouble, and they modified their ships not only for better cargo capacity, but also for greater speed and defenses. In order to evade Imperial patrols, smugglers often used smaller and less well-known [[Hyperspace route/Legends|routes]] that skirted Imperial strong points within the galaxy. There were many of these smuggling routes, and every smuggler usually had his or her preferred ways of getting from place to place safely. Despite their precautions, many smugglers ended their career on prison worlds such as [[Kessel/Legends|Kessel]] or [[Akrit'tar/Legends|Akrit'tar]]. Many smugglers were also killed during their runs&mdash;some even committed [[Death/Legends|suicide]] to avoid being arrested and sentenced.

==Behind the scenes==
The "Smuggler" was one of the original twenty-four character templates used by the ''[[Star Wars: The Roleplaying Game]]'', first published in the [[Star Wars: The Roleplaying Game (first edition)|first edition rulebook]].<ref name="RPG">[[Star Wars: The Roleplaying Game (first edition)|''Star Wars: The Roleplaying Game'']]</ref>

The smuggler is one of the classes in the video game ''[[Star Wars Galaxies]]'' and later used for the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] in the video game ''[[Star Wars: The Old Republic]]''.

